{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583360"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:14:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:14:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2644"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2644"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.53,0.12,0.27,0.07,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2644"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76673"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2644"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2644"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62170"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1098"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"2913"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3051"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3162"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6175"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43863"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76673"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with acute onset shortness of breath. She has been vomiting and has had diarrhoea (up to seven motions per day) for the last two days. Her partner has had similar gastrointestinal symptoms. She has had intermittent fevers and feels dehydrated. She has a medical history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, atrial fibrillation, and non-alcoholic fatty liver disease. Her regular medications include apixaban and a regular tiotropium/olodaterol inhaler.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Her chest sounds are clear and her heart sounds are dual. Her abdomen is soft and mildly tender diffusely. Investigations, including arterial blood gas results are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH: 7.2 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaO2: 80 mmHg (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaCO2: 34 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3: 17 mmol/L (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EK+: 3.0 mmol/L (3.5-4.9)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENa+: 130 mmol/L (137-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECl-: 107 mmol/L (100-109)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the abnormality demonstrated on the blood picture?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Normal anion gap metabolic acidosis with partial respiratory compensation","Normal anion gap metabolic acidosis without compensation","Raised anion gap metabolic acidosis with partial respiratory compensation","Raised anion gap metabolic acidosis without compensation","Respiratory acidosis with partial metabolic compensation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s blood results demonstrate a \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal anion gap metabolic acidosis with partial respiratory compensation\u003C/strong\u003E. Let\u0027s break down the key features:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pH of 7.2 indicates acidosis (normal range 7.35-7.45). The low bicarbonate (HCO3) of 17 mmol/L (normal range 22-26 mmol/L) points to a metabolic cause for the acidosis. The PaCO2 of 34 mmHg is below the normal range (35-45 mmHg), indicating respiratory compensation - the body is attempting to correct the acidosis by increasing the respiratory rate and blowing off CO2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo determine if this is a normal or raised anion gap metabolic acidosis, we calculate the anion gap: (Na+ + K+) - (HCO3- + Cl-). In this case: (130 + 3) - (17 + 107) = 9 mmol/L. A normal anion gap is typically less than 12 mmol/L, so this represents a normal anion gap metabolic acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal anion gap metabolic acidosis without compensation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because there is clear evidence of respiratory compensation (low PaCO2).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERaised anion gap metabolic acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E (with or without compensation) is incorrect because the calculated anion gap is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespiratory acidosis with partial metabolic compensation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the primary problem is metabolic (low bicarbonate) with respiratory compensation (low PaCO2), not the other way around.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely cause of this normal anion gap metabolic acidosis in this patient is gastrointestinal losses from diarrhoea. Other causes of normal anion gap metabolic acidosis include renal tubular acidosis, chloride excess (usually from intravenous fluid administration), and early renal failure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diarrhoea is a common cause of normal anion gap metabolic acidosis.","Normal anion gap metabolic acidosis is characterized by low pH, low bicarbonate, and normal anion gap.","Respiratory compensation for metabolic acidosis is indicated by a low PaCO2."],"references":["Bhandari R, Ekladious A, Javaid MM. Demystifying normal-anion-gap metabolic acidosis: pathophysiology, aetiology, evaluation and diagnosis. Intern Med J. 2024 Jul;54(7):1056-1065. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38837536/","Nickson, C. Anion gap. In: Life in the fast lane [online]. 2020 Nov 3 [Cited 2021 Jan 4]. Available at: https://litfl.com/anion-gap/","Hamilton PK, Morgan NA, Connolly GM, Maxwell AP. Understanding Acid-Base Disorders. Ulster Med J. 2017 Sep;86(3):161-166. Epub 2017 Sep 12. PMID: 29581626; PMCID: PMC5849971."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62170"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2644"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62170"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T05:09:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T05:09:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2644"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76673"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"gro